>
<p>Recently, I’ve read several articles on turning the 250sx into a 300sx. Seems everyone wants one and just needs to scrape the cash together for the conversion. Well if you are a woods rider like me, sometimes in the real world it’s too much of a good thing. Putting usable power to the ground is the desired result when it comes to technical climbs. Let’s call it grunt torque vs Horsepower.</p>
<p>I wanted a little more, read the articles and I took a 2011 250sx and installed the 300xc conversion. Torque increased I would say @ 10 % maybe 15%, but the hit was enormous. At $950 for the hardware and $250 for labor not cheap.The bike was a powerhouse for sure, but with drawbacks that had me re-thinking the cash outlay. Straight-line climbing was very exhilarating, but when technical climbs were the call, things became complicated. Any slick wet twisty terrain demanded complete focus to maintain hookup.</p>
<p>Once spinning,the beast was a handful to get back on track. In addition the engine had a tendency to heat up. My factory 250sx engines almost never boil over.</p>
<p>Back to the drawing board and I found a simple solution,from the Jeff Freddette archives. The pipe ring which is slipped into the cylinder opening between the pipe and head. This little goodie costs next to nothing and gave me just the low-to mid range boost I craved once I dialed it in. On High mapping wheel spin once again became a problem this little ring really is awesome!. Low mapping was the sweetspot though for technical tight twisty climbs. Once in the meat of the powerband the hit was noticeably more stout, but very controllable. Is it as good as the 300? Well, the 300 is an awesome machine right out of the box ,but the 250sx with the ring,and lighter rolling weight is pretty darn close with just my little secret.</p>
<p>Cheers</p>
<p>Mack</p>
